Macedonians decided in a referendum on whether to change their country’s name
The people of Macedonia decided in a referendum on Sunday whether their name would be changed to “Republic of North Macedonia,” a gesture that would resolve a decades-long conflict with Greece, which had blocked their candidacy for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbor is a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic population, a majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has questioned whether the participation will reach the minimum 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid.
The referendum paper raised the following question: "Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, claim that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies like the EU and NATO.
"Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, many Members of Parliament have said they will respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that no irregularities had been reported at one afternoon.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% of the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters deposited their vote.
"I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe," said 62-year-old Tanevski, who voted in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko deposited their vote in the Macedonian referendum on a country name change that would open the way to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
In front of parliament, in Skopie, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and removing chairs in front of tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
“We are in favour of entering NATO and the EU, but we want to do so with a very high head, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Euro-Asian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership would provide the investment that Macedonia so much needs, whose unemployment rate is above 20%.
“I think the vast majority will be in favor, as more than 80% of citizens are in favor of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said after depositing his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be a “confirmation of our future.”
In a survey published last Monday by the Institute of Policy Research, it was assured that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, which is less than required.
Another survey conducted by Telma TV from Macedonia revealed that 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour.
In order for the referendum to be considered a success, participation must be 50% plus one vote.
