"The sea belongs to us": a coastless Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the route to the Pacific
The sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings waves marine blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases show the motto: "The sea belongs to us by law,
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout Bolivia, a land without sea, they still vividly recall the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict for resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the yearning to sail again through the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the biggest in decades, as Bolivia expects a resolution from the International Court of Justice for October one, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, it is waiting for the outcome with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the decision of the International Court of Justice on large screens spread across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favour of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile will have an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is fighting a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has a lot to say about Monday’s resolution.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The United Nations agency based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the decision of the International Court of Justice came only six months after the final allegations indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
