John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools have a career of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes harvested in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it reaches his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the qualifying tables, with the highest rates of approvals in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages earned an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS centres, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages by considering them a fundamental competence that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, it is considered that as a subject, languages are at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent colleges and everywhere.
A 2014 survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills revealed that, among the reasons given by employers about the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17 per cent were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
The fact of being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically ahead of the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of over 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and it was found that the only two-digit language spoken, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centers will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in the independent schools, you will always be able to choose from several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this subject.
Scotland’s independent schools devote all of their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future owes them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication."
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
