North Korea says "there's no chance" they'll unilaterally disarm first if they don't trust
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions deepened his distrust in the United States and that there was no chance that his country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared before the international agency’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile testing, dismantling nuclear testing facilities, and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we did not receive any similar response from the United States,” he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances there’s no chance that we will disarm ourselves first unilaterally.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea's well-known complaints over Washington's resistance to a "phase-by-phase" denuclearization formula that rewards the country as he takes step-by-step steps, his statement is important as he did not simply reject a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons earlier.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization first and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even by objecting to a declaration of end of war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can cause us to fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the U.S. leader to the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: "If South Korea had been the interested party in denuclearization rather than the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stagnation."
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles toward US soil after the suicide-missile “evil president” Trump called Kim “rocket man.”
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving towards disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions were needed to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline set for this: "We can take two years, three years, or five months, no matter."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo reported to the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of the Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we make the definitive and fully verified denuclearization a reality.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang’s ballistic and nuclear missile programmes.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip wasn’t good.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but a few hours later, North Korea denounced that his “demands were those of a mafia.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States implemented “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had communicated to him that the “corresponding measures” he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
Thanks to a new course taught this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing male culture of studying all night by drinking caffeine.
One professor discovered that students of the world’s number one university usually have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, is believed to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
Their motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl approached and asked me why she just learned about this now, in her last year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of dreaming, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books that tell them about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are informed of how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know that it is not going to change student behavior instantly.
However, we believe they have the right to know, just like anyone has the right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” said Professor Czeisler.
He stated that the culture of pride for “spending the night on a wake” still exists, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure to which students are subjected meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, which is why they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He noted that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
He expects the next step to be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler’s recommendation is that students think about putting an alarm to bed and another to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble falling asleep.
