The National Trust spy on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been conducted in a state of the Scottish Highlands, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
Anything discovered is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide upcoming conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as Daubenton riverside bats and long-eared browns from the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile research with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of bat calls and what species do.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behavior.
NTS Nature Conservation Advisor Rob Dewar expects the results to reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
They are under threat by the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or domestic cat attacks.
Bats are not really blind.
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the subject of bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in the field, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated the first and only reserve dedicated to Scotland bats in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten species of bats.
The property director, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave, we have a fantastic bat area," he said.
“We have ancient buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there remains a lot of unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It emphasizes the importance of checking if there are bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, as a breeding colony can be unintentionally destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean to annihilate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
