Syria is ready for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and seeks help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been over seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions were improving.
“The situation on the ground is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees who had to leave it due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods are already met.
The UN estimates that, since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country and in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would appreciate the help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that promoted the insurgency.
